.lisp
.exdent 96 Examples:
#2a ((x y) (a b) ((uu 3) "VV"))
.exdent 96 produces a 3 by 2 array.  3(uu 3)* is one of the elements.
#2a ("foo" "bar")
.end_lisp
produces a 2 by 3 array whose elements are character objects.
Recall that a string is a kind of vector.
.lisp
#0a 5
.end_lisp
produces a rank-0 array whose sole element is 5.

.item #*
7#*2bbb*...* signifies a bit vector; 2bbb*... are the bits
(characters 31* or 30*).  A vector of type 3art-1b* is created
and filled with the specified bits, the first bit specified going in
array element 0.  The length is however many bits you specify.
Alternatively, specify the length with a decimal number between the
7#* and the 7**.  The last 31* or 30* specified is duplicated
to fill the additional bits.  Thus, 7#8*3*0101* is the same as 7#**301011111*.

.item #s
7#s(2type* 2slot* 2value* 2slot* 2value* 2slot* 2value* ...)*
constructs a structure of type 2type*.  Any structure type defined with
3defstruct* can be used as 2type* provided it has a standard constructor
taking slot values as keyword arguments.  (Standard constructors can be
functions or macros; either kind works for 7#s*.)  The slot names
and values appearing in the read syntax are passed to the constructor
so that they initialize the structure.  Example:
.lisp
(defstruct (foo :named)
  bar
  lose)
#s (foo :bar 5 :lose haha)
.end_lisp
produces a 3foo* whose 3bar* component is 5 and whose 3lose* component
is 3haha*.

.item #=
.item1 ##
'setq circular-structure-reading page
Are used to represent circular structure or shared structure.
7#2n*=* preceding an object ``labels'' that object with the label 2n*,
a decimal integer.  This has no effect on the way the object labeled
is read, but it makes the label available for use in a 7#2n*#* construct
within that object (to create circular structure) or later on (to create
shared structure).  7#2n*#* counts as an object in itself, and reads
as the object labeled by 2n*.  

For example, 7#1=*3(a . 7#1#*)* is a way of notating a circular list such
as would be produced by 3(circular-list 'a)*.  The list is labeled
with label 1, and then its cdr is given as a reference to label 1.
3(7#1=#:*foo 7#1#*)* is an example of shared structure.  An uninterned
symbol named 3foo* is used as the first element of the list, and
labeled.  The second element of the list is the very same uninterned
symbol, by virtue of a reference to the label.

Printing outputs 7#2n*=* and 7#2n*#* to represent circular or
shared structure when 3*print-circle* is non-3nil*.

.item #,
Evaluate a form at load time.
7#,2foo** evaluates 2foo* (the p.r. of a Lisp form) at read
time, except that during file-to-file compilation it is arranged
that 2foo* will be evaluated when the QFASL file is loaded.  This is a way,
for example, to include in your code complex list-structure constants that cannot
be written with 3quote*.  Note that the reader does not put 3quote*
around the result of the evaluation.  You must do this yourself if you
want it, typically by using the 3'* macro-character.  An example of 
a case where you do not want 3quote* around it is when this object is
an element of a constant list.

.item #.
7#.2foo** evaluates 2foo* (the p.r. of a lisp form) at read
time, regardless of who is doing the reading.

.item #`
7#`* is a construct for repeating an expression with some
subexpressions varying.  It is an abbreviation for writing several
similar expressions or for the use of 3mapc*.  Each subexpression
that is to be varied is written as a comma followed by a list of the
things to substitute.  The expression is expanded at read time into
a 3progn* containing the individual versions.
.lisp
#`(send stream ',(:clear-input :clear-output))
.end_lisp
expands into
.lisp
(progn (send stream :clear-input)
       (send stream :clear-output))
.end_lisp

Multiple repetitions can be done in parallel by using commas
in several subexpressions:
.lisp
#`(rename-file ,("foo" "bar") ,("ofoo" "obar"))
.end_lisp
expands into
.lisp
(progn (rename-file "foo" "ofoo")
       (rename-file "bar" "obar"))
.end_lisp

If you want to do multiple independent repetitions, you must use nested
7#`* constructs.  Individual commas inside the inner 7#`* apply to
that 7#`*; they vary at maximum speed.  To specify a subexpression
that varies in the outer 7#`*, use two commas.
.lisp
#`#`(print (* ,(5 7) ,,(11. 13.)))
.end_lisp
expands into
.lisp
(progn (progn (print (* 5 11.)) (print (* 7 11.)))
       (progn (print (* 5 13.)) (print (* 7 13.)))
.end_lisp

.item #o
7#o 2number** reads 2number* in octal regardless of the
setting of 3*read-base**.  Actually, any expression can be prefixed
by 7#o*; it is read with 3*read-base** bound to 8.

.item #b
Like 7#o* but reads in binary.

.item #x
Like 7#x* but reads in radix 16 (hexadecimal).  The letters 3a*
through 3f* are used as the digits beyond 9.

.item #r
7#2radix*r 2number** reads 2number* in radix 2radix* regardless
of the setting of 3*read-base**.  As with 7#o*, any expression
can be prefixed by 7#2radix*r*; it is read with 3*read-base**
bound to 2radix*.  2radix* must be a valid decimal integer between
2 and 36.

For example, 7#3r102* is another way of writing 311.* and
7#11r32* is another way of writing 335*.  Bases larger than ten use
the letters starting with 3a* as the additional digits.

.item #c
7#c(2real* 2imag*)* constructs a complex number with real part
2real* and imaginary 2part*.  It is equivalent to 32real*+2imag*i*,
except that 7#c* is allowed in Common Lisp syntax and the other is not.

.cindex conditionalization, read-time
.item #+
'setq sharp-plus page
This abbreviation provides a read-time conditionalization facility.  It
is used as 7#+2feature* 2form**.  If 2feature* is a symbol, then
this is read as 2form* if 2feature* is present in the list
3*features** (see (*features*-var)).  Otherwise, the construct is
regarded as whitespace.

Alternately, 2feature* may be a boolean expression composed of 3and*, 3or*, and
3not* operators and symbols representing items that may appear on
3*features**.  Thus,
7#+*3(or lispm amber)* causes the following object to be seen
if either of the features 3lispm* or 3amber* is present.

For example, 7#+*3lispm 2form** makes 2form* count if being read by Zetalisp,
and is thus equivalent to 7#q 2form**.  Similarly, 7#+*3maclisp 2form** is equivalent
to 7#m 2form**.  7#+*3(or lispm nil) 2form** makes 2form* count on either
Zetalisp or in NIL.

Here is a list of features with standard meanings:
.table 3
.item lispm
This feature is present on any Lisp machine (no matter what version of hardware
or software).

.item maclisp
This feature is present in Maclisp.

.item nil
This feature is present in NIL (New Implementation of Lisp).

.item mit
This feature is present in the MIT Lisp machine system,
which is what this manual is about.

.item symbolics
This feature is present in the Symbolics version of the Lisp machine system.
May you be spared the dishonor of using it.
.end_table

7#+*, and the other read-time conditionalization constructs that
follow, discard the following expression by reading it with
3*read-suppress** bound to 3t* if the specified condition is false.

.item #-
7#-2feature* 2form** is equivalent to 7#+*3(not 2feature*) 2form**.

.item #q
7#q 2foo** reads as 2foo* if the input is being read by
Zetalisp, otherwise it reads as nothing (whitespace).
This is considered obsolete; use 7#+*3lispm* instead.

.item #m
7#m 2foo** reads as 2foo* if the input is being read into Maclisp,
otherwise it reads as nothing (whitespace).
This is considered obsolete; use 7#+*3maclisp* instead.

.item #n
7#n 2foo** reads as 2foo* if the input is being read into NIL
or compiled to run in NIL, otherwise it reads as nothing (white space).
This is considered obsolete; use 7#+*3nil* instead.

.item #
7#*3* introduces an expression in infix notation.  3* should be used
to terminate it.  The text in between describes a Lisp object such as a symbol,
number or list but using a nonstandard, infix-oriented syntax.  For example,
.lisp
#x:y+car(a1[i,j])
.exdent 96 is equivalent to
(setq x (+ y (car (aref a1 i j))))
.end_lisp

It is not strictly true that the Lisp object produced in this way has to be
an expression.  Since the conversion is done at read time, you can use
a list expressed this way for any purpose.  But the infix syntax is designed
to be used for expressions.

For full details, refer to the file 3SYS: IO1; INFIX LISP*.

.item #<
This is not legal reader syntax.  It is used in the p.r. of objects that cannot
be read back in.  Attempting to read a 7#*3<* signals an error.

.item #
.setq horseshoe-read page
This is used in the p.r. of miscellaneous objects (usually named
structures or instances) that can be read back in.  7#*3* should be
followed by a typename and any other data needed to construct an
object, terminated with a 3*.  For example, a pathname might print as
.lisp
#FS:ITS-PATHNAME "AI: RMS; TEST 5"
.end_lisp
The typename is a keyword that 3read* uses to figure out how to read in
the rest of the printed representation and construct the object.  It is read in in
package 3user* (but it can contain a package prefix).  The resulting symbol
should either have a 3si:read-instance* property or be the name of a flavor
that handles the 3:read-instance* operation.

In the first case, the property is applied as a function to the typename
symbol itself and the input stream.  In the second, the handler for that
operation is applied to the operation name (as always), the typename
symbol, and the input stream (three arguments, but the first is implicit
and not mentioned in the 3defmethod*).  3self* will be 3nil* and
instance variables should not be referred to.
3si:print-readably-mixin* is a useful implementation the
3:read-instance* operation for general purposes; see
(si:print-readably-mixin-flavor).

In either case, the handler function should read the remaining data from
the stream, and construct and return the datum it describes.  It should
return with the 3* character waiting to be read from the input stream
(3:untyi* it if necessary).  3read* signals an error after it is returned
to if a 3* character is not next.

The typename can be any symbol with an appropriate property or flavor, not
necessarily related to the type of object that is created; but for clarity, it is good
if it is the same as the 3type-of* of the object printed.  Since the type symbol is
passed to the handler, one flavor's handler can be inherited by many other
flavors and can examine the type symbol read in to decide what flavor to
construct.

.item #|
7#|* is used to comment out entire pieces of code.  Such a comment
begins with 7#|* and ends with 7|#*.  The text in between should be
one or more properly balanced p.r.'s of Lisp objects, possibly
including nested 7#|...|#* comments.  This text is skipped over by the
reader, and does not contribute to the value returned by 3read*.
.end_table

.section Expression Output Functions
.setq expression-output section-page
.cindex printing
.cindex expression output

These functions all take an optional argument called 2stream*, which is
where to send the output.  If unsupplied 2stream* defaults to the value of
3*standard-output**.  If 2stream* is 3nil*, the value of
3*standard-output** (i.e. the default) is used.  If it is 3t*, the value of
3*terminal-io** is used (i.e. the interactive terminal).  This is all
more-or-less compatible with Maclisp, except that instead of the
variable 3*standard-output** Maclisp has several variables and complicated rules.
For detailed documentation of streams, refer to (streams).

.defun prin1 object &optional stream
Outputs the printed representation of 2object* to
2stream*, with escaping (see (escaping)).
2object* is returned.
.end_defun

.defun prin1-then-space object &optional stream
Like 3prin1* except that output
is followed by a space.
.end_defun

.defun print object &optional stream
Like 3prin1* except that output
is preceded by a carriage return and followed by a space.
2object* is returned.
.end_defun

.defun princ object &optional stream
Like 3prin1* except that the output is not escaped.  2object* is
returned.
.end_defun

.defun write object &key stream escape radix base circle pretty level length case gensym array
Prints 2object* on 2stream*, having bound all the printing flags according to the
keyword arguments if specified.  For example, the keyword argument 2array* specifies how
to bind 3*print-array**; if 2array* is omitted, the ambient value of 3*print-array**
is used.  This function is sometimes cleaner than binding a printing control variable
explicitly.  The value is 2object*.
.end_defun

.subsection Pretty-Printing Output Functions
.cindex formatting lisp code
.cindex pretty-printing
.cindex grinding

.c If we ever get a new grinder, this section will document how to
.c customize it and that sort of thing.

.defun pprint object &optional stream
3pprint* is like 3prin1* except that 3*print-pretty** is bound to 3t*
so that the grinder is used.  3pprint* returns zero values, just as
the form 3(values)* does.
.end_defun

.defmac grindef function-spec...
'setq grind page
Prints the definitions of one or more functions, with indentation to make the code
readable.  Certain other ``pretty-printing'' transformations are performed:  The 3quote*
special form is represented with the 3'* character.  Displacing macros are
printed as the original code rather than the result of macro expansion.
The code resulting from the backquote (3`*) reader macro is represented
in terms of 3`*.

The subforms to 3grindef* are the function specs whose
definitions are to be printed; the usual way 3grindef* is used
is with a form like 3(grindef foo)* to print the definition
of 3foo*.  When one of these subforms is a symbol, if
the symbol has a value its value is prettily printed also.  Definitions are
printed as 3defun* special forms, and values are printed as 3setq* special
forms.

If a function is compiled, 3grindef* says so and tries to find its
previous interpreted definition by looking on an associated property
list (see 3uncompile* ((uncompile-fun)).  This works only if the
function's interpreted definition was once in force; if the definition
of the function was simply loaded from a QFASL file, 3grindef* cannot
not find the interpreted definition.

With no subforms, 3grindef* assumes the same arguments as when it was
last called.
.end_defmac

.defun grind-top-level obj &optional width (stream 3*standard-output**) (untyo-p 3nil*) (displaced 3'si:displaced*) (terpri-p 3t*) notify-fun loc
Pretty-prints 2obj* on 2stream*, putting up to 2width* characters
per line.  This is the primitive interface to the pretty-printer.  Note that it does not
support variable-width fonts.  If the 2width* argument is supplied, it is how many
characters wide the output is to be.  If 2width* is unsupplied or 3nil*,
3grind-top-level* tries to figure out the natural width of the stream,
by sending a 3:size-in-characters* message to the stream and using the first
returned value.  If the stream doesn't handle that message, a width of 395.*
characters is used instead.

The remaining optional arguments activate various strange features and usually should not
be supplied.  These options are for internal use by the system and are documented
here for only completeness.
If 2untyo-p* is 3t*, the 3:untyo* and 3:untyo-mark* operations are
be used on 2stream*, speeding up the algorithm somewhat.  2displaced* controls the
checking for displacing macros; it is the symbol which flags a place that has been
displaced, or 3nil* to disable the feature.
If 2terpri-p* is 3nil*, 3grind-top-level* does
not advance to a fresh line before printing.

If 2notify-fun* is non-3nil*, it should be a function that to be
called with three arguments for each ``token'' in the pretty-printed
output.  Tokens are atoms, open and close parentheses, and reader macro
characters such as 7'*.  The arguments given to 2notify-fun* are the
token, its ``location'' (see next paragraph), and 3t* if it is an atom
or 3nil* if it is a character.

2loc* is the ``location'' (typically a cons) whose car is 2obj*.  As the
grinder recursively descends through the structure being printed, it keeps track
of the location where each thing came from, for the benefit of the 2notify-fun*.
This makes it possible for a program to correlate the printed output
with the list structure.  The ``location'' of a close parenthesis is 3t*, because
close parentheses have no associated location.
.end_defun

.subsection Non-Stream Printing Functions

.defun write-to-string object &key escape radix base circle pretty level length case gensym array
.defun1 prin1-to-string object
.defun1 princ-to-string object
Like 3write*, 3prin1* and 3princ*, respectively, but put the output in a string
and return the string (see (write-fun)).
