.section Expression Input Functions
.setq expression-input section-page
.cindex reading
.cindex expression input

Most expression input functions read characters from an input stream.
This argument is called 2stream*.  If unsupplied it
defaults to the value of 3*standard-input**.

All of these functions echo their input and permit editing if used on an
interactive stream (one which supports the 3:rubout-handler*
operation; see below.)

The functions accept an argument 2eof-option* or two arguments
2eof-error* and 2eof-value* to tell them what to do if end of file
is encountered instead of an object's p.r.  The functions that take
two 2eof-* arguments are the Common Lisp ones.

In functions that accept the 2eof-option* argument, if no argument
is supplied, an error is signaled at eof.  If the argument is
supplied, end of file causes the function to return that argument.  Note
that an 2eof-option* of 3nil* means to return 3nil* if the end of
the file is reached; it is 2not* equivalent to supplying no
2eof-option*.

In functions that accept two arguments 2eof-error* and 2eof-value*,
end of file is an error if 2eof-error* is non-3nil* or if it is unsupplied.
If 2eof-error* is 3nil*, then the function returns 2eof-value*
at end of file.

An error is always signaled if end of file is encountered in the middle
of an object; for example, if a file does not contain enough right
parentheses to balance the left parentheses in it.  Mere whitespace does
not count as starting an object.  If a file contains a symbol or a number
immediately followed by end-of-file, it can be read normally without
error; if an attempt is made to read further, end of file is encountered
immediately and the 2eof-* argument(s) obeyed. 

These end-of-file conventions are not completely compatible with
Maclisp.  Maclisp's deviations from this are generally considered to be
bugs rather than features.

For Maclisp compatibility, 3nil* as the 2stream* argument also means
to use the value of 3*standard-input**, and 3t* as the 2stream*
argument means to use the value of 3*terminal-io**.  This is only
advertised to work in functions that Maclisp has, and should not be
written in new programs.  Instead of the variable 3*standard-input**
Maclisp has several variables and complicated rules.  For detailed
documentation of streams, refer to (streams).

The functions below that take 2stream* and 2eof-option* arguments
can also be called with the stream and eof-option in the other order.
This functionality is only for compatibility with old Maclisp programs,
and should never be used in new programs.  The functions attempt to
figure out which way they were called by seeing whether each argument is
a plausible stream.  Unfortunately, there is an ambiguity with symbols:
a symbol might be a stream and it might be an eof-option.  If there are
two arguments, one being a symbol and the other being something that is
a valid stream, or only one argument, which is a symbol, then these
functions interpret the symbol as an eof-option instead of as a
stream.  To force them to interpret a symbol as a stream, give the
symbol an 3si:io-stream-p* property whose value is 3t*.

.defun read &optional stream eof-option rubout-handler-options
Reads the printed representation of a Lisp object
from 2stream*, builds a corresponding Lisp object, and returns
the object.  2rubout-handler-options* are used as options
for the rubout handler, if 2stream* supports one; see
(rubout-handler) for more information on this.
.end_defun

.defun cli:read &optional stream (eof-errorp 3t*) eof-value recursive-p
The Common Lisp version of 3read* differs only in how its arguments
are passed.

2recursive-p* should be non-3nil* when calling from the reader or
from the defining function of a read-macro character; that is, when
reading a subexpression as part of the task of reading a larger
expression.  This has two effects: the subexpression is allowed to share
7#2n*#* labels with the containing expression, and whitespace which
terminates the subexpression (if it is a symbol or number) is not
discarded.
.end_defun

.defun read-or-end &optional stream eof-option rubout-handler-options
Like 3read*, but on an interactive stream if the input is just
the character 3End* it returns the two values 3nil* and 3:end*.
.end_defun

.defvar read-preserve-delimiters
Certain printed representations given to 3read*, notably those of symbols
and numbers, require a delimiting character after them.  (Lists do not, because
the matching close-parenthesis serves to mark the end of the list.)
Normally 3read* throws away the delimiting character if it is whitespace,
but preserves it (using the 3:untyi* stream operation) if the character is
syntactically meaningful, since it may be the start of the next expression.

If 3read-preserve-delimiters* is bound to 3t* around a call to 3read*,
the delimiting character is never thrown away, even if it is whitespace.
This may be useful for certain reader macros or special syntaxes.
.end_defvar

.defun read-preserving-whitespace &optional stream (eof-errorp 3t*) eof-value recursive-p
Like 3cli:read* but binds 3read-preserve-delimiters* to 3t*.
This is the Common Lisp way of requesting the 3read-preserve-delimiters* feature.
.end_defun

.defun read-delimited-list char &optional stream recursive-p
Reads expressions from 2stream* until the character 2char* is seen
at top level when an expression is expected; then returns a list of
the objects read.  2char* may be a fixnum or a character object.
For example, if 2char* is 7#/]*, and the text to be read from
2stream* is 3a (b c)]* ...  then the objects 3a* and 3(b c)*
are read, the 3]* is seen as a terminator and discarded, and the
value returned is 3(a (b c))*.  2recursive-p* is as for
3cli:read*.  End of file within this function is always an error
since it is always ``within an object''--the object whose textual
representation is terminated by 2char*.

Note that use of this function does not cause 2char* to terminate
tokens.  Usually you want that to happen, but it is purely under the
control of the readtable.  So you must modify the readtable to make this
so.  The usual way is to define 2char* as a macro character whose
defining function just signals an error.  The defining function is not
called when 2char* is encountered in the expected context by
3read-delimited-list*; if 2char* is encountered anywhere else,
it is an unbalanced bracket and an error is appropriate.
.end_defun

.defun read-for-top-level &optional stream eof-option
This is a slightly different version of 3read*.  It differs from 3read*
only in that it ignores close-parentheses seen at top level,
and it returns the symbol 3si:eof* if the stream reaches end-of-file
if you have not supplied an 2eof-option* (instead of signalling
an error as 3read* would).  This version of 3read* is used in
the system's ``read-eval-print'' loops.
.end_defun

.defun read-check-indentation &optional stream eof-option
This is like 3read*, but validates the input based on indentation.
It assumes that the input data is formatted to follow the usual
convention for source files, that an open-parenthesis in column zero
indicates a top-level list (with certain specific exceptions).
An open-parenthesis in column zero encountered in the middle of a list
is more likely to result from close-parentheses missing before it than
from a mistake in indentation.

If 3read-check-indentation* finds an open-parenthesis
following a return character in the middle of a list, it
invents enough close-parentheses to close off all pending lists, and
returns.  The offending open-parenthesis is 3:untyi*'d so it can begin
the next list, as it probably should.  End of file in the middle of a
list is handled likewise.

3read-check-indentation* notifies the caller of the incorrect formatting
by signaling the condition 3sys:missing-closeparen*.  This
is how the compiler is able to record a warning about the missing
parentheses.  If a condition handler proceeds, 3read* goes ahead
and invents close-parentheses.

There are a few special forms that are customarily used around function
definitions--for example, 3eval-when*, 3local-declare*, and 3comment*.
Since it is desirable to begin the function definitions in
column zero anyway, 3read-check-indentation* allows a list to begin
in column zero within one of these special forms.  A non-3nil*
3si:may-surround-defun* property identifies the symbols for which this
is allowed.
.end_defun

.defvar read-check-indentation
This variable is non-3nil* during a read in which indentation is being
checked.
.end_defvar

.subsection Non-Stream Parsing Functions

The following functions do expression input but get the characters
from a string or a list instead of a stream.

.defun read-from-string string &optional eof-option (start 30*) end
The characters of 2string* are given successively
to the reader, and the Lisp object built by the reader is returned.
Macro characters and so on all take effect.  If 2string*
has a fill-pointer it controls how much can be read.

2eof-option* is what to return if the end of the string is reached, as
in 3read*.  2start* is the index in the string of the first
character to be read.  2end* is the index at which to stop reading;
that point is treated as end of file.

3read-from-string* returns two values; the first is the object read
and the second is the index of the first character in the string not read.
If the entire string was read, this is the length of the string.

.lisp
.exdent 96 Example:
(read-from-string "(a b c)") => (a b c) 1and* 7
.end_lisp
.end_defun

.defun cli:read-from-string string &optional (eof-errorp 3t*) eof-value &key (start 30*) end preserve-whitespace
The Common Lisp version of 3read-from-string* uses a different calling
convention.  The arguments mean the same thing but are arranged
differently.  There are three arguments with no counterparts:
2eof-errorp* and 2eof-value*, which are simply passed on to
3cli:read*, and 2preserve-whitespace*, which if non-3nil* means
that the reading is done with 3read-preserve-delimiters* bound to
3t*.
.end_defun

See also the 3with-input-from-string* special form ((with-input-from-string-fun)).

.defun parse-integer string &key (start 30*) end (radix 310.*) junk-allowed
Parses the contents of 2string* (or the portion from 2start* to 2end*) as a numeral
for an integer using the specified radix, and returns the integer.
Radices larger than ten are allowed, and they use letters as digits beyond 9.
Leading whitespace is always allowed and ignored.  A leading sign is also allowed
and considered part of the number.

When 2junk-allowed* is 3nil*, the entire specified portion of string
must consist of an integer and leading and trailing whitespace.
Otherwise, an error happens.

If 2junk-allowed* is non-3nil*, parsing just stops when a non-digit
is encountered.  The number parsed so far is returned as the first
value, and the index in 2string* at which parsing stopped is returned
as the second value.  This number equals 2end* (or the length of
2string*) if there is nothing but a number.  If non-digits are found
without finding a number first, the first value is 3nil*.  Examples:
.lisp
(parse-integer " 1A " :radix 16.) => 26.
(parse-integer " 15X " :end 3) => 15.
(parse-integer " -15X " :junk-allowed t) => -15. 3
(parse-integer " 15X ") => error!
.end_lisp
.end_defun

.defun readlist char-list
This function is provided mainly for Maclisp compatibility.
2char-list* is a list of characters.  The characters may be
represented by anything that the function 3character* accepts:
character objects, fixnums, strings, or symbols.  The characters are
given successively to the reader, and the Lisp object built by the
reader is returned.  Macro characters and so on all take effect.

If there are more characters in 2char-list* beyond those needed to
define an object, the extra characters are ignored.  If there are not
enough characters, some kind of 3sys:read-end-of-file* error is signaled.
.end_defun

.subsection Input Error Conditions

.defcondition sys:read-error (3sys:parse-error* 3error*)
This condition name classifies all errors detected by the reader per se.
Since 3sys:parse-error* is implied, all 3sys:read-error* errors
must provide the proceed type 3:no-action* so that automatic proceed
is possible if the error happens during compilation.  See (sys:parse-error-condition).

Since this condition name implies 3sys:parse-error* and 3error*, those
two are not mentioned as implications below when 3sys:read-error* is.
.end_defcondition

.defcondition sys:read-end-of-file (3sys:read-error* 3sys:end-of-file*)
Whenever the reader signals an error for end of file, the condition object
possesses this condition name.

Since 3sys:end-of-file* is implied, the 3:stream* operation on the
condition instance returns the stream on which end of file was reached.
.end_defcondition

.defcondition sys:read-list-end-of-file (3sys:read-end-of-file* 3sys:read-error* 3sys:end-of-file*)
This condition is signaled when 3read* detects end of file in the middle of a list.

In addition to the 3:stream* operation provided because
3sys:end-of-file* is one of the proceed types, the condition instance
supports the 3:list* operation, which returns the list read so far.

Proceed type 3:no-action* is provided.  If it is used, the reader
invents a close-parenthesis to close off the list.
Within 3read-check-indentation*, the reader signals the error only once,
no matter how many levels of list are unterminated.
.end_defcondition

.defcondition sys:read-string-end-of-file (3sys:read-end-of-file* 3sys:read-error* 3sys:end-of-file*)
This is signaled when 3read* detects end of file in the middle of a
string delimited by double-quotes.

The 3:string* operation on the condition instance returns the string
read so far.

Proceed type 3:no-action* terminates the string and returns.
If the string is within other constructs that are unterminated,
another end of file error is will be signaled later.
.end_defcondition

.defcondition sys:read-symbol-end-of-file (3sys:read-end-of-file* 3sys:read-error* 3sys:end-of-file*)
This is signaled when 3read* detects end of file within
a multiple escape construct.

The 3:string* operation on the condition instance returns the print
name read so far.

Proceed type 3:no-action* terminates the symbol and returns.
If the symbol is within other constructs that are unterminated,
another end of file error is will be signaled later.
.end_defcondition

.defcondition sys:missing-closeparen (3condition*)
This condition, which is not an error, is signaled when
3read-check-indentation* finds an open-parenthesis in column zero
within a list.

Proceed type 3:no-action* is provided.  On proceeding, the reader
invents enough close-parentheses to close off all the lists that are
pending.
.end_defcondition

.section The Readtable
.setq readtable section-page
.cindex readtable

The syntax used by the reader is controlled by a data structure called
the 2readtable*.  (Some aspects of printing are also controlled by the
readtable.)  There can be many readtables, but the one that is used is
the one which is the value of 3*readtable**.  A particular syntax can be
selected for use by setting or binding 3*readtable** to a readtable
which specifies that syntax before reading or printing.  In particular,
this is how Common Lisp or traditional syntax is selected.  The
readtable also controls the symbol substitutions which implement
the distinction between the traditional and Common Lisp versions of
functions such as 3subst*, 3member*and 3defstruct*.

The functions in this section allow you to modify the syntax of
individual characters in a readtable in limited ways.  You can
also copy a readtable; then you can modify one copy and leave
the other unchanged.

A readtables may have one or more names.  Named readtables are
recorded in a central data base so that you can find a readtable by
name.  When you copy a readtable, the new one is anonymous and is not
recorded in the data base.

.defvar readtable
.defvar1 *readtable*
The value of 3readtable* or 3*readtable** is the current readtable.
This starts out as the initial standard readtable.  You can bind this
variable to change temporarily the readtable being used.

The two names are synonymous.
.end_defvar

.defconst si:standard-readtable
This is copied into 3*readtable** every time the machine is booted.
Therefore, it is normally the same as 3*readtable** unless you make
3*readtable** be some other readtable.  If you alter the contents of
3*readtable** without setting or binding it to some other readtable,
this readtable is changed.
.end_defconst

.defconst si:initial-readtable
The value of 3si:initial-readtable* is a read-only copy of the default
current readtable.  Its purpose is to preserve a copy of the standard
read syntax in case you modify the contents of 3*readtable** and regret
it later.  You could use 3si:initial-readtable* as the
2from-readtable* argument to 3copy-readtable* or
3set-syntax-from-char* to restore all or part of the standard syntax.
.end_defconst

.defconst si:common-lisp-readtable
A readtable which initially is set up to define Common Lisp read syntax.
Reading of Common Lisp programs is done using this readtable.
.end_defconst

.defconst si:initial-common-lisp-readtable
A read-only copy of 3si:common-lisp-readtable*, whose purpose is to
preserve a copy of the standard Common Lisp syntax in case you modify
3si:common-lisp-readtable* (such as, by reading a Common Lisp program
which modifies the current readtable).
.end_defconst

.defun si:rdtbl-names readtable
Returns the list of names of 3readtable*.
You may 3setf* this to add or remove names.
.end_defun

.defun si:find-readtable-named name
Returns the readtable named 3name*, or 3nil* if none is recorded.
.end_defun

.defun readtablep object
3t* if 2object* is a readtable.
.end_defun

The user can program the reader by changing the readtable in any of three ways.
The syntax of a character can be set to one of several predefined possibilities.
A character can be made into a 2macro character*, whose interpretation
is controlled by a user-supplied function which is called when the character is read.
The user can create a completely new readtable, using the readtable compiler
(3SYS: IO; RTC LISP*) to define new kinds of syntax and to assign syntax classes to
characters.  Use of the readtable compiler is not documented here.

.defun copy-readtable &optional from-readtable to-readtable
2from-readtable*, which defaults to the current readtable, is copied.
If 2from-readtable* is 3nil*, the standard Common Lisp syntax is
copied.  If 2to-readtable* is unsupplied or 3nil*, a fresh copy is
made.  Otherwise 2to-readtable* is clobbered with the copied syntax.

Use 3copy-readtable* to get a private readtable before using the following
functions to change the syntax of characters in it.  The value of 3*readtable**
at the start of a Lisp Machine session is the initial standard readtable, which
usually should not be modified.
.end_defun

.defun set-syntax-from-char to-char from-char &optional to-readtable from-readtable
Copies the syntax of 2from-char* in 2from-readtable* to character
2to-char* in 2to-readtable*.  2to-readtable* defaults to the
current readtable and 2from-readtable* defaults to 3si:initial-standard-readtable*
(standard traditional syntax).
.end_defun

.defun cli:set-syntax-from-char to-char from-char &optional to-readtable from-readtable
Is a Common Lisp function which copies the syntax of 2from-char* in
2from-readtable* to character 2to-char* in 2to-readtable*.
2to-readtable* defaults to the current readtable and
2from-readtable* defaults to 3si:initial-common-lisp-readtable*
(standard Common Lisp syntax).

Common Lisp has a peculiar idea of what it means to copy the syntax of a character.
The only aspect of syntax that the readtable supposedly specifies is the choice among
.table 7 0 300
.item *
token constituent:
digits, letters, random things like 3@*, 3!*, 3$*, and also colon!
.item *
whitespace:
spaces, 3Tab*, 3Return*.
.item *
single escape character:
3/* traditionally, 3\* in Common Lisp.
.item *
multiple escape character:
vertical-bar.
.item *
macro character:
standardly 3()",.'`;*
.item *
nonterminating macro character:
3#* is the only such character standardly defined.
.end_table

The differences among macro characters are determined entirely by the
functions that they invoke.  The differences among token constituents
(including the difference between 3A* and colon) are fixed!  You
can make 3A* be a macro character, or whitespace, or a quote
character, but if you make it a token constituent then it always behaves
the way it normally does.  You can make colon be a macro character,
or whitespace, etc., but if it is a token constituent it always
delimits package names.  If you make open-parenthesis into a token
constituent, there is only one kind of token constituent it can be (it
forces the token to be a symbol, like 3$* or 3@* or 3%*).

This is not how Lisp Machine readtables really work, but since
3cli:set-syntax-from-char* is provided just for Common Lisp, the
behavior specified by Common Lisp is laboriously provided.  So, if
2from-char* is some kind of token constituent, this function makes
2to-char* into a token constituent of the kind that 2to-char* is
supposed to be--not the kind of token constituent that 2from-char* is.

By contrast, the non-Common-Lisp 3set-syntax-from-char* would make
2to-char* have exactly the same syntactic properties that
2from-char* has.
.end_defun

.defun set-character-translation from-char to-char &optional readtable
Changes 2readtable* so that 2from-char* will be translated to 2to-char* upon
read-in, when 2readtable* is the current readtable.
This is normally used only for translating lower case letters to upper case.
Character translation is inhibited by escape characters and within strings.
2readtable* defaults to the current readtable.
.end_defun

.need 1800
.nopara
The following syntax-setting functions are more or less obsolete.

.defun set-syntax-from-description char description &optional readtable
Sets the syntax of 2char* in 2readtable* to be that described by the
symbol 2description*.  2readtable* defaults to the current readtable.

Each readtable has its own set of descriptions which it defines.
The following descriptions are defined in the standard readtable:
.table 3 0 1500
.item si:alphabetic
An ordinary character such as `3A*'.
.item si:break
A token separator such as `3(*'.  (Obviously left parenthesis has other
properties besides being a break.
.item si:whitespace
A token separator that can be ignored, such as `3 *'.
.item si:single
